{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.18,0.12,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8400"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48802"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3841"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"8503"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20241"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EType I endometrial carcinomas are the most common form of endometrial cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a risk factor for Type I endometrial carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obesity","Early menopause","Multiparity","Regular exercise","Low body mass index"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EType I endometrial carcinoma is strongly associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eunopposed oestrogen exposure, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich stimulates endometrial hyperplasia and increases cancer risk. Type I endometrial carcinomas are oestrogen-dependent adenocarcinomas. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E increases peripheral conversion of androgens to oestrogen in adipose tissue, increasing oestrogen exposure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly menopause\u003C/strong\u003E is not a risk factor - late menopause increases lifetime estrogen exposure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiparity\u003C/strong\u003E is protective due to progesterone exposure during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular exercise\u003C/strong\u003E is protective by reducing obesity and oestrogen levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow body mass index\u003C/strong\u003E is protective by reducing peripheral oestrogen production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther risk factors include nulliparity, polycystic ovary syndrome, tamoxifen use, and oestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type I endometrial carcinomas are estrogen-dependent adenocarcinomas associated with unopposed oestrogen exposure","Major risk factors include obesity, nulliparity, late menopause, and polycystic ovary syndrome","Type I endometrial cancers account for 80% of endometrial carcinomas and have a better prognosis than Type II"],"references":["Restaino S, Paglietti C, Arcieri M, Biasioli A, Della Martina M, Mariuzzi L, Andreetta C, Titone F, Bogani G, Raimondo D, Perelli F, Buda A, Petrillo M, Greco P, Ercoli A, Fanfani F, Scambia G, Driul L, Vizzielli G; The Udine Hospital Gynecological-Oncological Tumor Board Group. Management of Patients Diagnosed with Endometrial Cancer: Comparison of Guidelines. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Feb 8;15(4):1091. doi: 10.3390/cancers15041091. PMID: 36831434; PMCID: PMC9954548","Mahdy H, Casey MJ, Vadakekut ES, et al. Endometrial Cancer. [Updated 2024 Apr 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525981/","Makker V, MacKay H, Ray-Coquard I, Levine DA, Westin SN, Aoki D, Oaknin A. Endometrial cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2021 Dec 9;7(1):88. doi: 10.1038/s41572-021-00324-8. PMID: 34887451; PMCID: PMC9421940"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48802"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48802"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T15:08:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T15:08:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8400"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i